          "text": "Good question. Let me analyze the relay architecture across the roadmap versions.\n\n## Current structure\n\nThe roadmap already describes a unified relay pattern but doesn't name it:\n\n| Version | Ingress | Egress | Queue |\n|---------|---------|--------|-------|\n| v0.6 | HTTP (LAN peer) | HTTP (Quorum) | relay queue |\n| v0.7 | BLE | HTTP (Quorum) | **same** relay queue |\n| v0.8 | LoRa | HTTP (Quorum) | **same** relay queue |\n\nv0.6's architecture note already says: *\"Future transports (BLE, LoRa) will reuse the relay queue and egress logic, with transport-specific ingress. Build concrete first, extract abstraction later.\"*\n\n## Assessment\n\nThe abstraction is already implicit — v0.7 and v0.8 literally say \"deposits into the same relay queue as HTTP\" and \"same relay egress as v0.6.\" But the roadmap frames it as \"LAN Relay\" with BLE/LoRa bolted on, when it's actually:\n\n**Store-and-Forward Relay** = transport-agnostic queue + pluggable ingress + HTTP egress to Quorum\n\nThe \"Starlink Relay\" scenario in v0.8 is the clearest proof: it's HTTP ingress (from Quorum) → relay queue → LoRa egress. That's the *reverse* direction, and it still fits the same pattern.\n\n## What I'd actually change\n\n**Not much.** The roadmap's \"build concrete first\" approach is correct. Renaming v0.6 to \"Store-and-Forward\" would obscure the user-facing feature (LAN peers helping during partial outages). The concrete milestone should stay LAN-focused.\n\nWhat's worth doing:\n\n1. **Add a brief architectural callout** in v0.6 that names the relay queue as a first-class component (not just a footnote), since v0.7 and v0.8 depend on it\n2. **Simplify v0.7/v0.8 relay sections** — currently they each re-explain the pattern. Instead, reference the relay queue from v0.6 and just specify the new ingress adapter\n3. **In the whitepaper**, the relay architecture deserves its own subsection under Transport Layer (currently section 10 only describes the mailbox nod